## 3. Ownership — The Central Concept

Every smart pointer is built around **ownership**: the right and responsibility to delete an object.

The three questions that determine which smart pointer to use:
1. Should exactly **one** thing own this object? → `unique_ptr`
2. Should **multiple** things share ownership? → `shared_ptr`
3. Do I need to **observe** without owning? → `weak_ptr`

Ownership is not the same as access. Many things can read/write an object via raw pointers or references — but only the owner is responsible for freeing it.

---

## 4. unique_ptr — Exclusive Ownership

### Ownership model
Exactly one `unique_ptr` owns the managed object at any time. When it goes out of scope, the object is deleted automatically.

### Move semantics
`unique_ptr` is **move-only** — it cannot be copied, because that would create two owners. Ownership can be transferred (moved) but not shared.

```cpp
auto p1 = std::make_unique<int>(10);
auto p2 = p1;            // COMPILE ERROR — copy deleted
auto p2 = std::move(p1); // OK — ownership transferred, p1 = null
```

After a move, the source is set to `nullptr`. Dereferencing it is undefined behavior.

### Zero overhead
`unique_ptr` has exactly zero runtime overhead over a raw pointer. It is purely a compile-time safety mechanism.

### Custom deleters
`unique_ptr` accepts a second template parameter — a deleter — so it can manage any resource, not just heap memory (file handles, mutex locks, GPU buffers).

```cpp
auto f = std::unique_ptr<FILE, decltype(&fclose)>(fopen("x.txt","r"), &fclose);
```

### Key operations

```cpp
auto p = std::make_unique<int>(10);

*p;                         // dereference
p.get();                    // raw pointer (don't delete it!)
p->member;                  // arrow operator

auto p2 = std::move(p);     // transfer ownership; p is now null
int* raw = p2.release();    // p2 is null; you own raw now (must delete!)
p2.reset();                 // deletes and sets to null
p2.reset(new int(99));      // deletes old, takes new
```

---

## 5. shared_ptr — Shared Ownership

### Ownership model
Multiple `shared_ptr` instances can point to the same object. The object is destroyed when the **last** owner is destroyed or reset. Managed via **reference counting**.

```cpp
auto p1 = std::make_shared<int>(42);
auto p2 = p1;   // both own it, ref count = 2

p1.reset();     // ref count = 1, still alive
p2.reset();     // ref count = 0 → object deleted
```

### The control block
When a `shared_ptr` is created, it allocates a **control block** on the heap. The control block stores:
- `ref_count` — how many `shared_ptr` instances own this object
- `weak_count` — how many `weak_ptr` instances observe this object
- The deleter and allocator (if custom)

Every copy atomically increments `ref_count`. Every destruction atomically decrements it. When it hits zero, the managed object is destroyed. The control block lives until `weak_count` also hits zero.

### make_shared vs shared_ptr(new T)

```cpp
auto p1 = std::make_shared<Foo>(args);   // ONE heap allocation  ← prefer this
auto p2 = std::shared_ptr<Foo>(new Foo); // TWO heap allocations
```

`make_shared` allocates the object and control block together — faster, better cache locality. Always prefer it.

### Thread safety
The reference count is **atomic** — thread-safe. But the **object itself** is not protected. You still need a mutex if two threads write to the same object.

### Overhead vs unique_ptr
- Two pointer members instead of one
- Atomic increment/decrement on every copy and destruction
- Two heap allocations if not using `make_shared`

Use `unique_ptr` by default. Reach for `shared_ptr` only when shared ownership is genuinely needed.

