## 6. weak_ptr — Non-Owning Observer

### The problem it solves — cyclic references
If two objects each hold a `shared_ptr` to the other, ref counts never reach zero and memory is never freed.

```cpp
struct Node { std::shared_ptr<Node> next; };

auto a = std::make_shared<Node>();
auto b = std::make_shared<Node>();
a->next = b;   // rc(b) = 2
b->next = a;   // rc(a) = 2
// both go out of scope: rc drops to 1, never 0 → memory leak forever
```

### What weak_ptr does
`weak_ptr` points to an object managed by `shared_ptr` but **does not affect `ref_count`**. It increments only `weak_count`, which keeps the control block alive but allows the object to be freed when `ref_count` hits zero.

### Expiry and lock()
Because `weak_ptr` doesn't keep its object alive, the object might be deleted while the `weak_ptr` still exists. To access it safely, call `.lock()`:
- Returns a `shared_ptr` if the object is still alive (temporarily bumps ref count)
- Returns `nullptr` if the object has been freed

```cpp
// WRONG — race condition: object might die between check and use
if (!wp.expired()) use(*wp);

// RIGHT — atomic check + access
if (auto sp = wp.lock()) use(*sp);
```

### Fix the cycle with weak_ptr

```cpp
struct Node {
    std::shared_ptr<Node> next;  // forward link: strong ownership
    std::weak_ptr<Node>   prev;  // backward link: non-owning — cycle broken
};
```

---

## 7. Object Lifetime vs Control Block Lifetime

| Event | Object destroyed? | Control block destroyed? |
|---|---|---|
| ref_count → 0 | Yes | Not yet |
| weak_count → 0 | — | Yes |
| Both → 0 | Yes | Yes |

The control block outlives the object when `weak_ptr` instances still exist. This is why `weak_ptr` can correctly report `.expired() == true` — the control block is still there to be queried even though the object is gone.

