## 10. Best Practices

**Always use make_unique / make_shared** — never expose raw `new`.
```cpp
auto p = std::make_shared<Foo>(a, b);   // correct
std::shared_ptr<Foo> p(new Foo(a, b));  // avoid
```

**Pass by raw pointer or reference when no ownership is transferred.**
```cpp
void process(MyClass* obj) { ... }  // doesn't own, just uses
process(sp.get());                  // extract raw pointer
process(*sp);                       // or pass by reference
```

**Never manage the same object with two independent shared_ptrs.**
```cpp
int* raw = new int(5);
shared_ptr<int> p1(raw);
shared_ptr<int> p2(raw);  // UNDEFINED BEHAVIOUR — double free!
```

**Use unique_ptr by default. Reach for shared_ptr only when the design genuinely requires shared ownership.** The most common mistake is defaulting to `shared_ptr` because it feels "safer." `unique_ptr` expresses stronger intent and has zero overhead.

**Use weak_ptr for back-pointers, caches, and observer patterns** — anything that needs to watch an object without keeping it alive.

---

## 11. Decision Guide

```
Need heap memory?
│
├── One clear owner → unique_ptr   (zero overhead, always default)
│
├── Multiple shared owners → shared_ptr   (ref-counted)
│       │
│       └── Cycle or non-owning ref needed? → weak_ptr
│
└── No ownership, just access → raw pointer or reference
                                (never delete through these)
```